external_knowledge:
- "activities wrapped up" refers to tasks in the status 'completed'.;
- "team members" refers to users who have created the tasks. They are identified by the `user_id`.;
- "in the last month" means tasks created within the last 30 days.;
- "summary of the latest releases" includes the release ID, version, and type. These are key details to understand the context of each release.;
- "manager's name" highlights the individual in charge of the release, which typically guides the team working on it. The names are a way to identify who is responsible for overseeing the work.

sql:
SELECT u.user_id, t.assigned_to
FROM users u
JOIN tasks t ON u.user_name = t.assigned_to;

SELECT * 
FROM release_candidates
WHERE MOD(candidate_id, 2) = 1;

SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM branches
WHERE is_active = 1 AND branch_name != '19';

external_knowledge:
'Critical issues' are those that have been marked with a priority level of 'critical' in the issue tracking system. This indicates the highest level of urgency that requires immediate attention.;
The release version and branch name together give a comprehensive view of the software's current stage of development and its respective branch.;
The 'release managers' are individuals responsible for overseeing the release process, ensuring that software versions meet quality standards before deployment.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM release_candidates
WHERE is_active = 1;

SELECT r.release_version, r.actual_date, r.status, rm.name AS manager_name
FROM releases AS r
JOIN release_managers AS rm ON r.release_manager_id = rm.release_manager_id;

SELECT rm.name, rm.email
FROM release_managers rm
WHERE rm.release_manager_id IN (
  SELECT rc.created_by
  FROM release_candidates rc
)
AND rm.release_manager_id IN (
  SELECT r.release_manager_id
  FROM releases r
);
